50|$|The battery also powered the camera's coupled 'match-needle' {{exposure}} metering system. This {{consisted of}} two needles pointing along a vertical <b>shutter-speed</b> <b>scale</b> visible in the viewfinder. In manual mode, a black needle pointed out the shutter speed recommended by the built-in 60/40 percent centerweighted, cadmium sulfide (CdS) light meter, while a translucent green needle showed the current (actual) shutter speed setting of the camera. The photographer would then adjust the shutter speed and/or the lens aperture until the needles aligned, at which point correct exposure would be achieved.|$|E

